22:01.086 --> 22:06.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mustafa Badreddine was believed
to be the
main military commander of
Hezbollah forces

22:06.492 --> 22:12.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fighting in Syria. In life, he
was a villain
to America and its allies. In
death, he is

22:12.464 --> 22:16.268 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a hero to these people.

22:16.368 --> 22:21.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Hezbollah neighborhoods of
Beirut, the
funerals of war dead feel like
celebrations.

22:21.473 --> 22:25.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Women throw rice and rose petals
on the coffin
as it passes.

22:25.311 --> 22:31.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"I know there are martyrs in
Syria," this
woman says, "but we like that
and we are happy

22:31.283 --> 22:35.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because we give martyrdom. If we
didn't go
to Syria, ISIS would come to
here."

22:36.055 --> 22:45.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: When the name of this dead
man is in
our minds, we will always
remember that we

22:45.798 --> 22:49.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have to fight. We have to get
revenge from
those who killed him.

22:49.268 --> 22:53.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Badreddine was
believed to
have been involved in the
devastating attack

22:53.339 --> 23:01.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the U.S. Marine barracks in
Beirut in 1983,
which killed 241 Americans. He
was also indicted

23:01.313 --> 23:07.886 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
for the assassination of
Lebanese Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri in a huge truck
bomb in 2005.

23:07.987 --> 23:12.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was killed in Syria leading
Hezbollah's
military campaign, propping up
the group's

23:12.625 --> 23:19.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ally President Bashar al-Assad.
Young men
from here often go to fight in
Syria for Hezbollah,

23:19.398 --> 23:24.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many returning in coffins. It's
a heavy price
the group is paying for its
involvement in

23:24.670 --> 23:26.572 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
the war.

23:26.672 --> 23:31.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The death of this commander,
however, is the
biggest loss to the group since
his predecessor

23:31.243 --> 23:35.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was killed in 2008. Mustafa
Badreddine, according
to Hezbollah, had said just a
few months ago

23:36.081 --> 23:43.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that he would only return to
Lebanon from
Syria either victorious or as a
martyr.

23:43.656 --> 23:48.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Professor Daniel Byman of
Georgetown University
says he was a founding member of
Hezbollah.

23:48.527 --> 23:52.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL BYMAN, Georgetown
University: Badreddine's
death is a big blow to
Hezbollah. He's someone

23:52.731 --> 23:58.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who was there at the founding of
the movement.
He's been with it in leadership
positions,

23:58.304 --> 24:01.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really the tip of the sphere
almost everywhere
they have been active, whether
it's been in

24:01.573 --> 24:04.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Kuwait, in Lebanon, now in
Syria.

24:05.010 --> 24:10.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is a tremendous blow.
It has repeatedly
lost senior leaders in its
history, and it

24:10.416 --> 24:15.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has repeatedly emerged strong
and committed.
So, it's not likely to change
things in the

24:15.354 --> 24:17.222 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
country.

24:17.323 --> 24:20.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: It's not clear
who was responsible
for his death. Badreddine would
have been

24:20.626 --> 24:26.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a target for both Israel and
extremist groups
fighting in Syria, like ISIS.

24:26.398 --> 24:31.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hezbollah leaders say Badreddine
was killed
in a huge explosion in Damascus
and that they're

24:31.603 --> 24:36.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
investigating who was behind the
attack. They
expect to make an announcement
in the coming

24:36.942 --> 24:38.010 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
days.

24:38.110 --> 24:45.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Jane
Ferguson
in Beirut.

24:45.217 --> 24:54.727 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

24:54.827 --> 24:59.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
Mark Shields
and Michael Gerson analyze the
week's news;

24:59.531 --> 25:03.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and how advances in genetic
sequencing is
saving lives.

25:03.902 --> 25:09.475 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, first, the latest
installment in our
series Broken Justice about new
approaches

25:09.575 --> 25:11.410 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to criminal justice.

25:11.510 --> 25:16.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we have a conversation
with a noted
lawyer and author on questions
of sentencing,

25:17.049 --> 25:21.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
overcrowding in prisons and
whether a series
of changes around the country go
far enough.

25:21.854 --> 25:25.224 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown traveled to
Alabama for our
report.

25:25.324 --> 25:31.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The Equal Justice
Initiative
in Montgomery, Alabama, a
nonprofit founded

25:31.997 --> 25:38.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in 1989 by lawyer and civil
rights activist
Bryan Stevenson to represent
death row prisoners

25:38.570 --> 25:44.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and indigent and juvenile
defendants who he
argues have been denied
effective representation,

25:44.643 --> 25:46.812 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
often due to racial bias.

25:46.912 --> 25:52.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In recent years, which included
the publication
of an acclaimed memoir, "Just
Mercy," Stevenson

25:52.618 --> 25:56.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has become a leading voice
nationally for
criminal justice reform.

25:56.622 --> 26:02.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I met him at his office in
Montgomery while
reporting on Alabama's
overcrowded prisons

26:02.494 --> 26:04.496 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and spike in prison violence.

26:04.596 --> 26:07.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON, Founder, Equal
Justice Initiative:
There were less than 5,000
people in Alabama's

26:07.232 --> 26:10.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
prisons throughout most of the
1970s.

26:10.369 --> 26:16.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then you had politicians
like you had
all over the country get
captivated, I'm going

26:16.241 --> 26:19.244 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to say intoxicated, by the
politics of fear.

26:19.344 --> 26:21.280 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Intoxicated.

26:21.380 --> 26:24.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BRYAN STEVENSON: Yes,
intoxicated by the politics
of fear and anger. They began
competing with

26:24.249 --> 26:28.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
each other over who could be the
toughest
on crime, and putting people in
prison became

26:28.954 --> 26:31.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the solution to virtually every
problem.

26:31.356 --> 26:35.160 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Drug addiction and drug
dependency, which
could have been seen as a health
issue, was

26:35.260 --> 26:40.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
seen as a crime issue. The
growing freedom
that was emerging in the Deep
South for African-Americans,

26:40.699 --> 26:45.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who until just a decade earlier
couldn't vote,
couldn't go into schools, had to
be regulated.

26:45.804 --> 26:50.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we used the criminal justice
system, and
you saw this massive increase in
the number

26:50.509 --> 26:52.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of people sent to jails or
prisons.

26:52.411 --> 26:58.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we went from about 5,000
people in the
1970s to 30,000 people today in
a state with

26:58.951 --> 27:03.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about 4.5 million people. That's
an unbelievably
high rate of incarceration.

27:03.755 --> 27:08.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you're seeing
this -- you're
seeing our incarceration system
as a continuation

27:08.560 --> 27:12.097 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of slavery, of a history of
racial injustice
in the country.

27:12.197 --> 27:17.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON: Well, I think
it's a continuation
of using crime narrative to
control social

27:17.369 --> 27:21.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and political dynamics that
can't be controlled
in more legitimate ways.

27:22.074 --> 27:26.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we created this so-called
war on drugs,
and we targeted people of color,
and we got

27:26.245 --> 27:30.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
everybody to buy into the fact
that if we
don't put these dangerous people
into jails

27:30.249 --> 27:35.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and prisons, we are none safe.
And that's
how we went nationwide from a
prison population

27:35.153 --> 27:41.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of about 300,000 in the 1970s to
2.3 million
today. And now we have the
highest rate of

27:41.660 --> 27:43.362 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
incarceration in the world.

27:43.462 --> 27:47.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And here in
Alabama, an extreme
model of it.

27:47.699 --> 27:49.501 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BRYAN STEVENSON: Exactly.

27:49.601 --> 27:54.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's rooted in this comfort
level with
reducing people to their worst
act and acting

27:54.273 --> 28:00.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in very extreme, harsh, punitive
ways. I mean,
a state that was shaped by
lynching as a response

28:00.846 --> 28:09.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to things like interracial sex,
or organizing
for better sharecropping
conditions, to use

28:09.288 --> 28:15.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lynching, calling these people
criminals,
has created a culture, an
environment where

28:15.794 --> 28:20.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then putting people in prison
for life with
no chance of parole for writing
a bad check

28:20.666 --> 28:23.502 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
or being in possession of
marijuana didn't
seem so radical.

28:23.602 --> 28:28.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Last year,
Alabama's Republican
legislature and governor passed
a law to reform

28:28.907 --> 28:34.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some of Alabama's sentencing
guidelines and
increase probation and parole
supervision.

28:34.446 --> 28:39.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Stevenson believes such measures
here and
elsewhere don't go nearly far
enough.

28:39.217 --> 28:46.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON: I think people
realize that
we're spending way too much
money on jails

28:46.191 --> 28:51.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and prisons. And I think that's
true in Alabama.
It's true nationwide. We went
from $6 billion

28:51.330 --> 28:55.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
spent on jails and prisons in
the United States
in 1980 to $80 billion last
year.

28:55.867 --> 29:00.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the recession was terrible
for everybody,
for everything, except criminal
justice reform,

29:00.205 --> 29:04.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because, all of a sudden, state
legislators
had to start asking harder
questions about

29:04.176 --> 29:08.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
why we're spending so much money
to keep people
in jails or prison who are not a
threat to

29:08.747 --> 29:10.716 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
public safety.

29:10.816 --> 29:13.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you think
it's more a concern
out of money than anything else
that is leading

29:14.019 --> 29:16.588 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to whatever discussion there is
about changes?

29:16.688 --> 29:19.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON: Well, I think
that's the
primary motivation. I do.

29:19.625 --> 29:23.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we were a more affluent
today, if we had
more resources, I don't think
we'd have the

29:23.462 --> 29:30.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
same interest. Too many people
in this state,
too many people in this country
don't care

29:30.168 --> 29:35.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if people who are in jails or
prisons are
abused. They don't care if
they're raped.

29:35.273 --> 29:38.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They don't care if they are
murdered. They
don't care if they're assaulted.
They don't

29:38.610 --> 29:40.345 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
care about their victimization.

29:40.445 --> 29:46.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, because of that, we haven't
responded
the way a just society, a decent
society is

29:46.251 --> 29:51.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
supposed to respond when you see
abuse and
murder and rape and misconduct.

29:51.690 --> 29:56.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, if you had
your opportunity,
given where things are at right
now, what

29:56.962 --> 29:59.898 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is the one -- what's the most
important thing
that needs to happen?

29:59.998 --> 30:01.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON: Can I do two?

30:01.333 --> 30:03.101 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: OK.

30:03.201 --> 30:08.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON: I will -- the
two things
that I would do, I would commit
to reducing

30:08.240 --> 30:12.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the prison population by 5,000
people. Just
put out an arbitrary number like
that.

30:12.744 --> 30:14.546 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Where do those
people go?

30:14.646 --> 30:19.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON: They will go
home. We have
5,000 people in our jails and
prisons that

30:19.518 --> 30:24.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
could go home tomorrow that
wouldn't in any
way threaten public safety.

30:24.923 --> 30:29.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you know who could help us
identify those
5,000 are the wardens at these
prisons. If

30:29.327 --> 30:34.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you said to any warden in the
state of Alabama,
can you identify 50, 100, 200
people in your

30:34.599 --> 30:38.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prison who you think could go
home tomorrow,
wouldn't be a problem, most of
them could

30:38.437 --> 30:40.072 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
do it in a heartbeat.

30:40.172 --> 30:46.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We could get to that 5,000
number just like
that. And then we could take the
money we

30:46.178 --> 30:53.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
save, the significant money that
we save,
and invest in better caregiving,
better management.

30:53.552 --> 30:59.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have to have people running
prisons that
care about the incarcerated,
that are smart,

30:59.958 --> 31:08.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that aren't bullies, that aren't
reactionary,
that aren't kind of vindictive.
And then you

31:09.067 --> 31:10.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
could begin to see improved
conditions.

31:10.902 --> 31:14.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Are you more
optimistic nationally,
when you look at the large
picture?

31:14.506 --> 31:17.576 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON: I'm cautiously
optimistic.

31:17.676 --> 31:23.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But punishment is a local issue.
And the national
discourse will only have an
impact on places

31:23.982 --> 31:29.488 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
like Alabama if people in
Alabama step up.
But I am generally hopeful. I
don't think

31:29.588 --> 31:33.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's going to happen by itself,
and what I'm
worried about is that Congress
might pass

31:33.959 --> 31:39.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a few reforms, we might see
reforms here and
there, and we're going to
declare victory,

31:39.664 --> 31:43.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and three years from now, the
prison population
will have decreased by 1
percent, and we will

31:43.668 --> 31:45.971 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
still be the most punitive
nation on the planet.

31:46.071 --> 31:51.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Stevenson now has
a broader
educational project under way,
erecting markers

31:51.443 --> 31:56.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to remind people of a history
often ignored,
and his group is collecting
samples of earth

31:56.515 --> 32:01.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from the sites of lynchings,
with an aim toward
creating memorials around the
state.

32:01.553 --> 32:03.989 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I asked Stevenson what drives
him.

32:04.089 --> 32:08.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRYAN STEVENSON: Well, I think,
when you see
what I see, you don't have a
choice. I think,

32:08.760 --> 32:14.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if most people saw what I see,
they'd have
the same instinct, they'd have
the same idea,

32:14.166 --> 32:17.102 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that we have to fix this,
because it's unconscionable.

32:17.202 --> 32:22.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have kids, 15- and 16-year-
old kids, that
we're still putting in adult
jails and prisons

32:22.474 --> 32:26.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Alabama. And what happens to
those children
is that they get abused, they
get assaulted.

32:26.778 --> 32:31.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I don't think that there's a
decent person
watching this program that, if
they saw that,

32:31.316 --> 32:33.652 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wouldn't feel like, we have got
to stop that.

32:33.752 --> 32:44.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From Montgomery, Alabama, I'm
Jeffrey Brown
for the "PBS NewsHour."

32:44.129 --> 32:56.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
